                <div class="modern-grid">
                    <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                    <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">


                        <h4 class="type-30-light m-type-21-light">
                            If you’re considering an <a href="https://www.saratoga.ca.us/DocumentCenter/View/1630/Accessory-Dwelling-Unit-Regulations-PDF" target="_blank">accessory dwelling unit (ADU) in Saratoga</a>, it’s important to understand the local regulations. Saratoga generally follows California’s statewide ADU standards, with a few city-specific rules to keep in mind.

                        </h4>

                            <div class="spacer-100 l-spacer-80 m-spacer-72"></div>
                    </div>
                </div>


                    <div class="modern-grid">
                        <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                        <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                            <div class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                <p>An ADU is a self-contained living space that shares a lot with a primary home. It can be attached, detached, or created by converting existing space.</p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>




                    <div class="modern-grid">
                        <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                        <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                            <div class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                <p>Read on to learn everything you need to know about the requirements for building an ADU in Saratoga and <a href="https://www.samara.com">how Samara can help you get it done</a>.</p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>




                <div class="modern-grid">
                    <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                    <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                                <div class="spacer-64 m-spacer-50"></div>


                        <h2 class="type-36 m-type-30">
                            Saratoga ADU regulations at a glance

                        </h2>

                            <div class="spacer-36 m-spacer-24"></div>
                    </div>
                </div>


                    <div class="modern-grid">
                        <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                        <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                            <div class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                <p>Saratoga offers a streamlined ADU permitting process. The city will provide <a href="https://www.saratoga.ca.us/439/Accessory-Dwelling-Units" target="_blank">initial feedback on an ADU permit submission within 15</a> days, and most projects with complete applications are approved within the state-mandated 60-day window. In practice, the full permitting process—including plan review and revisions—typically takes three to four months.</p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>




                    <div class="modern-grid">
                        <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                        <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                            <div class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                <p>Saratoga generally follows California’s ADU laws but includes a few local rules on height, setbacks, and design that may affect your plans.</p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>




                <div class="modern-grid">
                    <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                    <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                                <div class="spacer-36 m-spacer-24"></div>


                        <h3 class="type-24-light">
                            Size and lot requirements

                        </h3>

                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                    </div>
                </div>


                    <div class="modern-grid">
                        <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                        <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                            <div class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                <p>Size, height, and placement requirements vary by the type of ADU:</p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>




                <div class="modern-grid">
                    <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                    <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                        <ul class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                    <li>
                                        <strong>Detached ADUs</strong> can be up to 1,200 square feet. Height is capped at 16 feet by default, or 18 feet if the property is within a half mile of public transit or on a multi-family lot. An additional two feet may be allowed to match the primary home’s roof pitch.
                                            <div class="spacer-16"></div>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <strong>Attached ADUs</strong> can be up to 1,200 square feet, or 50 percent of the main home’s living area, whichever is less. They can be as tall as the primary home, up to a maximum of 25 feet.
                                            <div class="spacer-16"></div>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <strong>Junior ADUs (JADUs)</strong> must be located within the walls of the existing or proposed home and are limited to 500 square feet.
                                    </li>
                        </ul>
                        <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                    </div>
                </div>



                    <div class="modern-grid">
                        <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                        <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                            <div class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                <p>Most ADUs must be set back at least four feet from the rear and side property lines. If your ADU replaces a structure that was demolished, and is built in the same footprint and dimensions, setbacks of less than four feet may be allowed.</p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>




                    <div class="modern-grid">
                        <div class="column-3 l-column-2 m-column-0"></div>
                        <div class="column-6 l-column-8 m-column-6 newsroom-internal-body">
                            <div class="type-18-light m-type-15">
                                <p>Saratoga also permits ADUs under 800 square feet to be built in the front setback if no other compliant location exists.</p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="spacer-24 m-spacer-16"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>




